no-redundant-contextual-parameter-type

Errors when a callback parameter repeats a type that is already supplied by the
surrounding context.

Source: custom rule for lintcn

The Problem

Agents often restate callback parameter types even when TypeScript already knows
them from the target function type. That adds noise and makes callbacks harder
to scan without adding safety.

What Gets Flagged

  declare function useRunner(fn: (ctx: { command: string }) => void): void

  useRunner((ctx: { command: string }) => {
    ctx.command
  })

  tool({
    execute: async (ctx: { command: string }) => {
      await bash.exec(ctx.command)
    },
  })

What Is Allowed

  useRunner((ctx) => {
    ctx.command
  })

  const execute = (ctx: { command: string }) => {
    ctx.command
  }

  declare function withValue<T>(fn: (value: T) => void): void
  withValue((value: string) => {
    value.toUpperCase()
  })

Notes

  - The current rule only checks arrow functions and function expressions
  - It skips generic inference cases where the annotation can influence `T`
  - It does not flag standalone functions or object literal methods
